### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Description

Hey! 

I've started to play with the new resource (by the way: great!). I'm not sure if this is intended, but I found a bit strange the following difference: 
```ts
const url = `https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos?_limit=5`;

// no http-request
r1 = resource({
  request: () => undefined,
  loader: async () => {
    const res = await fetch(url);
    return res.json();
  },
});

// will fire an http-request
r2 = resource({
  loader: async () => {
    const res = await fetch(url);
    return res.json();
  },
});
```
I was actually expecting both cases to behave the same way. In particular, I was expecting to trigger `r2` manually with `reload`. Here is a stackblitz showing the difference: https://stackblitz.com/edit/stackblitz-starters-h5jgum?file=src%2Fmain.ts 

Again: I apology in advance if I'm missing something obvious! 

### Please provide the exception or error you saw

```ts
const url = `https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos?_limit=5`;

// no http-request
r1 = resource({
  request: () => undefined,
  loader: async () => {
    const res = await fetch(url);
    return res.json();
  },
});

// no http-request
r2 = resource({
  loader: async () => {
    const res = await fetch(url);
    return res.json();
  },
});
```

This change contains multiple cleanups in the AppComponent:
- remove unused code;
- use router input bindings instead of manual read from the active route;
- remove isBrowser checks from even handlers (click events should not be invoked on the server, right?)

Resolved an issue where the use of `esbuild`'s `inject` feature caused incorrect reordering of class structures during bundling. This reordering affected extended classes, as illustrated below:

```js
class e extends Ur {
  constructor(n, r, i) {
    super(n, r, i);
  }
  ngOnDestroy() {
    this.flush();
  }
  static Éµfac = function (r) {
    return new (r || e)(pe(Xe), pe(Ti), pe(Di));
  };
  static Éµprov = oe({ token: e, factory: e.Éµfac });
}

var Ur = class {
  // Class properties and methods omitted for brevity
};
```

By reducing the reliance on `inject`, we ensure that the ordering of class properties and methods remains consistent, preserving the expected behavior.

Closes #28941

